data.content:
Here's the improved version using MSTest's specialized collection assertions:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    Assert.IsNotEmpty(users);
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive));
    Assert.HasCount(3, users);
    Assert.ContainsSingle(users.Where(u => u.Role == "Admin"));
}
```

**What changed and why:**

| Before | After | Benefit |
|---|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0)` | `Assert.IsNotEmpty(users)` | Failure says "collection was empty" instead of "expected True" |
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count() == 3)` | `Assert.HasCount(3, users)` | Failure shows "expected 3, got 5" |
| `Single()` + `Assert.IsTrue(x != null)` | `Assert.ContainsSingle(...)` | Throws a clear assertion failure instead of `InvalidOperationException` |

The `Assert.IsTrue(users.All(...))` line is fine — there's no built-in "assert all match predicate" method, so `IsTrue` is appropriate there.

The general rule: **prefer specialized assertions over `Assert.IsTrue`** — they produce meaningful failure messages that tell you *what* went wrong without needing a debugger.
